## Migration: `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationToken` + `Task`

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** starting in .NET 5. The entire thread-abort mechanism was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally`, mid-`lock`, or mid-`catch`, leaving resources permanently leaked.

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, but respect the timeout.
            // task.Wait(timeout) would also work, but we already
            // armed the CTS with the timeout above.
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates so callers see the real type.
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    // Convenience overload when the work is already async.
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Callers must change too

```csharp
// OLD (.NET Framework) — fire-and-forget, no cooperation needed:
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowQuery(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// NEW (.NET 8) — pass the token through:
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => SlowQuery(ct), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

The callee checks `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or passes it to APIs like `HttpClient.GetAsync(url, ct)`, `DbCommand.ExecuteReaderAsync(ct)`, etc.

---

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced kill** | Unlike `Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` ignores the token, it runs forever. There is no safe replacement for hard-abort. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` compiles but throws** | The API still exists (for compat) but always throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Delete all references. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` is dead** | It's never thrown. Catch blocks for it are unreachable dead code. |
| **Fire-and-forget leaks** | If you cancel but don't `await`/`Wait()` the task, exceptions go unobserved and the work may keep running, burning CPU. |
| **`Task.Result` vs `GetAwaiter().GetResult()`** | `.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`; `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` rethrows the original. The migrated code uses the latter for cleaner stack traces. |
| **Signature is breaking** | `Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>`. Every call site must be updated. If you need a back-compat shim: |

```csharp
// Back-compat shim (token is ignored — work can't be cancelled!)
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    return ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => work(), timeout);
}
```

> ⚠️ The shim lets code compile, but the work **will keep running** past the timeout since nothing checks the token. Use it only as a stepping stone.
